name: interpreted-geologic-history-of-the-sedro-woolley-north-and-lyman-7-5-minute-quadrangles-wester
notes:
Interpreted geologic history of the Sedro-Woolley North and Lyman 7.5-minute quadrangles, western Skagit County, Washington, Open File Report  2000-1.This report presents our interpretation of the geologic history of a significant portion of the lower Skagit Valley, focusing on t.he area in and near the Sedro-Woolley North and Lyman 7.S-minute quadrangles. Our interpretation is based on detailed geologicmapping in and around the Bow, Alger, Sedro-Woolley North, and Lyman 7.S-minute quadrangles from 1997 to 1999 (FIg. 1). We also present some of our structural and geochemical data from the 1996/97 study of the Kendall and Deming 7.S-minute
quadrangles (Fig. 1). This report heavily cites and should be accompanied by a companion report-the geologIc map of the Sedro-Woolley North and Lyman quadrangles (Dragovich and others, 1999). Both reports borrow information from several ongoing studies that are outgrowths of our current mapping. These
studies include: (1) Everson Interstade glacIal sedImentary facies analysis and mapping, (2) mapping and structural analyses of the nappe emplacement deformation in the Northwest Cascades system, and (3) mapping, dating, and 3-D modeling of the massive Skagit Valley lahar(s). Downloadable zip file includes Plate 1 and Text (PDF) for Open File Report  2000-1.
